The paper discusses a game-theoretic approach to network slicing, which suggests that it belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT) category. The paper also deals with resource allocation in multi-tenant networks, which falls under the Networked Systems (cs.NI) and Systems and Control (cs.SI) categories. The paper also discusses the efficiency and fairness of the resulting allocations, which suggests that it belongs to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category. Finally, the paper deals with the practical implementation of network slicing, which falls under the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category.
